# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana-fritter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] ABC-Clio provides service to fifteen different online databases which contain over one million online textbooks.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The company consults academic leaders in the fields they cover in order to provide authority for their reference titles.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The headquarters are located in Santa Barbara, California.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] ABC-Clio was founded in 1955 as a privately held corporation by Eric Boehm with its first publication, *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The name represents the company's two original divisions when it incorporated in 1969: ABC stands for American Bibliographical Center and Clio Press is named after Clio, the muse of history from ancient Greek mythology.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] According to Boehm, he had always been interested in history so when he noticed that there were not many good historical abstracting services available, he started publishing the *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] During the 1960s, a sister bibliographic and abstract publication on American history was added, *America: History and Life*, which was considered an award-winning title.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The company entered into digital publishing with electronic data in the 1960s and in 1975, it published its first online database called *DIALOG*.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] During the 1980s, ABC-Clio expanded into providing primary reference books such as encyclopedias and dictionaries and stopped publishing bibliographic books.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In the 1990s, ABC-Clio began to provide access to its humanities database on CD-ROM.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The *Exegy Current Events* CD-ROM was named "Best Disc of the Year" by Library Journal.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 1998, ABC-Clio provided electronic access to *America: History and Life*.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] By the 2000s, one of the company's most popular products had become online databases for researching many topics in the field of the humanities.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 2001, ABC-Clio began to publish eBooks, initially providing 150 different titles to schools and libraries.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The company's reference books had won numerous awards, and the company started a series of subject-related online databases for secondary school use.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 2004, the company acquired the quarterly historical journal, *Journal of the West*, which has been published since 1962.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 1996, ABC-Clio merged with an electronic publishing company, Intellimation, which also produced educational software.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The merger brought Becky Snyder, who by 2009 had become ABC-Clio's president, from Intellimation.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 2007, it sold two databases – *Historical Abstracts* and *America: History and Life* – to EBSCO Publishing; in addition, the companies also agreed a partnership through which nine additional ABC-Clio databases would be distributed through EBSCO Publishing.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing acquired ABC-Clio for US$22.9 million (equivalent to $26.1 million in 2024).
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 2008, ABC-Clio acquired the Greenwood Publishing Group from Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The deal gave ABC-Clio a "perpetual license" to use the imprints of Greenwood Press and publish all of its titles.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] Acquiring the publishing group gave ABC-Clio access to Greenwood Press, Praeger Publishers, Praeger Security International, and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] Greenwood focuses on publishing full-text reference works which are authoritative on various topics.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] Libraries Unlimited came to ABC-Clio as part of a deal with Greenwood Press.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 2012, Kathyrn Suárez was named publisher for this division, which focuses on publishing for librarians and information professionals.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] ABC-Clio databases are provided under the umbrella of ABC-Clio Solutions.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] There are fifteen different databases providing access to different subject areas.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] ABC-Clio Solutions provides digital curriculum with multimedia content, text-to-speech features, translation tools which covers various topics relating to history and the humanities.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] After ABC-Clio acquired Greenwood Press's databases, they revamped the look and feel of their interface in order to provide common access through the ABC-Clio interface.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] ABC-Clio also provided the ability to search across multiple databases through one search, also providing options for narrowing the search after revamping their interface.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] The new interface is considered user-friendly and provides access to personalized features.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] Originally publishing books by disillusioned former Communists who had fled from behind the Iron Curtain, the publishing house became known for publishing "scholarly and professional books" in the subject areas of social sciences and the humanities.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 1966, Praeger sold his firm to William B.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] Benton, an American senator and publisher and the chairman of *Encyclopaedia Britannica*.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] In 1976, it was sold to CBS, which had shortened the name to Praeger Publishing before selling it to Greenwood Press, Inc., in 1986.
[src:banana-fritter/abc-clio] When the renamed Greenwood Publishing Group (GPG) was acquired by ABC-Clio in 2009, Praeger Publishing became a standalone imprint of ABC-Clio, and remained such when, in December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:banana-fritter/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:banana-fritter/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:banana-fritter/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:banana-fritter/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:banana-fritter/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:banana-fritter/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The **culture of Africa** is varied and manifold, consisting of a mixture of countries with various peoples depicting their unique characteristic and trait from the continent of Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] It is a product of the diverse populations that inhabit the continent of Africa and the African diaspora.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Generally, Culture can be defined as a collective mass of distinctive qualities belonging to a certain group of people.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] These qualities include laws, morals, beliefs, knowledge, art, customs, and any other attributes belonging to a member of that society.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Culture is the way of life of a group of people.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Africa has numerous ethnic nationalities all with varying qualities such as language, dishes, greetings, dressing, dances and music.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] However, each of the regions of Africa share a series of dominant cultural traits which distinguish various African regional cultures from each other and the rest of the world.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] For example, social values, religion, morals, political values, economics, and aesthetic values all contribute to various African cultures.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Expressions of culture are abundant within Africa, with large amounts of cultural diversity being found not only across different countries but also within single countries.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Africa has influenced and been influenced by other continents.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] This can be portrayed in the willingness to adapt to the ever-changing modern world rather than staying rooted in their static culture.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The Westernized few, persuaded by American culture and Christianity, first denied African traditional culture, but with the increase of African nationalism, a cultural recovery occurred.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The governments of most African nations encourage national dance and music groups, museums, and to a lower degree, artists and writers.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] 90% to 95% of Africa's cultural heritage is held outside of Africa by large museums.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In a BBC report on defining factors of identity, "50-60% of British black African/Caribbean respondents, agreed that ethnicity played a key role, the largest of any group.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The singular viewpoint of ‘black’ as an ‘identifier’ or an ‘ethnicity’ not only denies cultural differences between the population, it also denies the nuance within a vastly diverse community….
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African cultures, which originated on the continent of Africa, have several distinct differences than that of Black culture, which is originated by African Americans in the United States after they were stripped of most of their own African cultures during enslavement.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] During the Roman colonization of North Africa (parts of Algeria, Libya, Egypt, and the whole of Tunisia), provinces such as Tripolitania became major producers of food for the republic and the empire.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] This generated much wealth in these places for their 400 years of occupation.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] During colonialism in Africa, Europeans possessed attitudes of superiority and a sense of mission.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The French accepted an African as French if that person gave up their African culture and adopted French ways.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Knowledge of the Portuguese language and culture and abandonment of traditional African ways defined one as civilized.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Kenyan social commentator Mwiti Mugambi argues that the future of Africa can only be forged from accepting and mending the sociocultural present.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] For Mugambi, colonial cultural hangovers, pervasive Western cultural inundation, and aid-giving arm-twisting donors are, he argues, here to stay and no amount of looking into Africa's past will make them go away.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Africa has a rich tradition of arts and crafts.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African arts and crafts find expression in a variety of woodcarvings, brass and leather artworks.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African arts and crafts also include sculpture, paintings, pottery, ceremonial and religious headgear and dress.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Maulana Karenga states that in African art, the object was not as important as the soul force behind the creation of the object.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] He also states that All art must be revolutionary, and in being revolutionary, it must be collective, committing, and functional.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The meaning behind what he said can simply be interpreted as black art serving an actual purpose in the direction of a revolutionary change.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Black art should not be done simply for "arts sake" but should rather be a means by which artists make a vast change through a medium that awakens, strengthens, and provides inspiration for a massive change within the black community.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Certain African cultures have always emphasized personal appearance, and jewelry has remained an important personal accessory.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Many pieces of such jewelry are made of cowry shells and similar materials.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Similarly, masks are made with elaborate designs and are an important part of some cultures in Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Masks are used in various ceremonies depicting ancestors and spirits, mythological characters, and deities.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In many traditional arts and craft traditions in Africa, certain themes significant to those particular cultures recur, including a couple, a woman with a child, a male with a weapon or animal, and an outsider or a stranger.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Couples may represent ancestors, community founders, married couples, or twins.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The couple theme rarely exhibits the intimacy of men and women.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The mother with the child or children reveals the intense desire of the women to have children.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The theme is also representative of mother mars and the people as her children.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The man with the weapon or animal theme symbolizes honor and power.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] A stranger may be from some other tribe or someone from a different country, and a more distorted portrayal of the stranger indicates a proportionately greater gap from the stranger.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] These are all popular interpretations of African craft and art.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Like all human cultures, African folklore and religion represents a variety of social facets of the various cultures in Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Like almost all civilizations and cultures, flood myths have been circulating in different parts of Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Culture and religion share space and are deeply intertwined in African cultures.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In Ethiopia, Christianity and Islam form the core aspects of Ethiopian culture and inform dietary customs and rituals and rites.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] According to a myth among Central African foragers, Chameleon, hearing a strange noise in a tree, cut open its trunk, and water came out in a great flood that spread all over the land.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Folktales also play an important role in many African cultures.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Stories reflect a group's cultural identity, and preserving the stories of Africa will help preserve an entire culture.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Storytelling affirms pride and identity in a culture.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In Africa, stories are created by and for the ethnic group telling them.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Different ethnic groups in Africa have different rituals or ceremonies for storytelling, which creates a sense of belonging to a cultural group.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] To outsiders hearing an ethnic group's stories, it provides an introspection and insight into the beliefs, views, and customs of the community.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] For people within the community, it allows them to encompass their group's uniqueness.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] They show the human desires and fears of a group, such as love, marriage, and death.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Folktales are also seen as a tool for education and entertainment.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Folklore provides the wisdom to understand certain moments from different perspectives and it also showcases that all of our problems and successes happen in every culture and throughout different periods of history.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] They provide a way for children to understand the material and social environment.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Every story has a moral to teach people, such as goodwill prevail over evil.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] For entertainment, stories are set in fantastic, non-human worlds.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Often, the main character of the story would be a talking animal, or something unnatural would happen to a human character.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Even though folktales are for entertainment, they bring a sense of belonging and pride to communities in Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] There are different types of African stories: animal tales and day-to-day tales.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Animal tales are more oriented towards entertainment but still have morals and lessons to them.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Animal tales are normally divided into trickster tales and ogre tales.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In animal tales, a certain animal would always have the same character or role in each story, so the audience does not have to worry about characterization.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The popular roles for some animals are as follows; The Hare was always the trickster, clever and cunning, while the Hyena was always tricked by the Hare.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Ogres are always cruel, greedy monsters.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The messengers in all the stories were the Birds.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Day-to-Day tales are the most serious tales, never including humor, that explained the everyday life and struggles of an African community.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] These tales take on famine, escape from death, courtship, and family matters, using a song form when the climax of the story was being told.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African stories all have a certain structure to them.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Villagers would gather around a common meeting place at the end of the day to listen and tell their stories.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Storytellers had certain commands to start and end the stories, "Ugai Itha" to get the audience's attention and begin the story, and "Rukirika" to signal the end of a tale.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Each scene of a story is depicted with two characters at a time, so the audience does not get overwhelmed.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In each story, victims can overcome their predators and take justice out on the culprit.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Certain tools were used in African folktales.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] For example, idiophones, such as drums, were used to make the sounds of different animals.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Repetition and call-back techniques in prose or poem were also used to get the audience involved in the stories.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Women's traditional clothes in Ethiopia are made from cloth called *schema* and are used to make *habesha kemis*.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The latter garment (habesha kemis) is basically cotton cloth, about 90 cm wide, woven in long strips which are then sewn together.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Sometimes shiny threads are woven into the fabric for an elegant effect.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Men wear pants and a knee-length shirt with a white collar, and perhaps a sweater.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Men often wear knee-high socks, while women might not wear socks at all.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Men, as well as women, wear shawls, the *netela*.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Zulus wear a variety of attire, both traditional for ceremonial or culturally celebratory occasions.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Traditional male clothing is usually light, consisting of a two-part apron (similar to a loincloth) used to cover the genitals and buttocks.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The front piece is called the *umutsha* (pronounced Zulu pronunciation: [umtifash]) and is usually made of springbok or other animal hide twisted into different bands which cover the genitals.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The rear piece, called the I*bheshu* [ibeːʃu], is made of a single piece of springbok or cattle hide, and its length is usually used as an indicator of age and social position; longer amabheshu (plural of ibheshu) are worn by older men.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Married men will usually also wear a headband, called the *umqhele* [umǃʰɛle], which is usually also made of springbok hide, or leopard hide by men of higher social status, such as chiefs.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Zulu men will also wear cow tails as bracelets and anklets called *imishokobezi* [imiʃoɠoɓɛːzi] during ceremonies and rituals, such as weddings or dances.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In the Muslim parts of Africa, daily attire also often reflects Islamic tradition.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The traditional attire for the Muslim men usually covers a minimum of the head and the range between the waist of the man and the knees, while the dress code for the islamic women is made to conceal and cover the hair and the body from the neck down to the ankles.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] There are some Muslim women who also conceal their face.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Nevertheless, there are some Muslims that believe that the Quran does not command that women should wear a hijab or a burqa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The various cuisines of Africa use a combination of locally available fruits, cereal grains and vegetables, as well as milk and meat products.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features a preponderance of milk, curd and whey products.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In much of tropical Africa, however, cow's milk is rare and cannot be produced locally (owing to various diseases that affect livestock).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The continent's diverse demographic makeup is reflected in the many different eating and drinking habits, dishes, and preparation techniques of its manifold populations.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] However it is important to consider the affordability of and access of these products on daily basis.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In Central Africa, the basic ingredients are plantains and cassava.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Fufu-starchy foods (usually made from fermented cassava roots) are served with grilled meat and sauces.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Many local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes like spinach stew, cooked with tomato, peppers, chillis, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Another favorite is Bambara, a porridge of rice, peanut butter, and sugar.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, monkey, antelope and warthog are also served occasionally.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The cuisine of the African Great Lakes region varies from area to area.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping people is distinctive in that meat products are generally absent.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Cattle, sheep and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth and are not generally consumed as food.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In some areas, traditional people consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Elsewhere, other peoples are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali, the East African version of West Africa's fufu.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In Uganda, steamed, green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Ethiopian cuisine and Eritrean cuisine are *tsebhis* (stews) served with *injera* (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum), and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentil, faba beans).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The related Somali cuisine consists of an exotic fusion of diverse culinary influences.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Varieties of *bariis* (rice), the most popular probably being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] *Xalwo* (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (*lubaan*) or incense (*cuunsi*), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a *dabqaad*.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to ancient Egypt.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] To add to the confusion, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a "tajine" dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian "tajine" is a baked omelet/quiche-like dish).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations – there's the sophisticated, full-bodied flavours of Moroccan palace cookery, the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine, and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The cooking of Southern Africa is sometimes called 'rainbow cuisine', as the food in this region is a blend of many culinary traditions, including those of the Khoisan, Bantu, European and Asian populations.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas and papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] However, there are some more western style puddings, such as the Angolan Cocada amarela, which was inspired by Portuguese cuisine.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Meat products include lamb, as well as game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The seafood includes a wide variety such as crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] A typical West African meal is heavy with starchy items, meat, spices, and flavors.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including those of Fufu, Banku and Kenkey (originating from Ghana), Foutou, Couscous, Tô, and Garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, but also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The staple grain or starch varies from region to region and ethnic group to ethnic group.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] However, corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Banku and Kenkey are maize dough staples, and Garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Examples of these include Benachin from The Gambia and Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Traditional Sub-Saharan African music is as diverse as the region's various populations.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The common perception of Sub-Saharan African music is that it is rhythmic music centered on the drums, and indeed, a large part of Sub-Saharan music, mainly among speakers of Niger–Congo and Nilo-Saharan languages, is rhythmic and centered on the drum.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Sub-Saharan music is polyrhythmic, usually consisting of multiple rhythms in one composition such as the Serer of Senegambia's ultra-religious njuup tradition (the progenitor of mbalax).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Dance involves moving multiple body parts.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] These aspects of Sub-Saharan music were transferred to the new world by enslaved West Africans and can be seen in its influence on music forms as Samba, Jazz, Rhythm and Blues, Rock & Roll, Salsa, and Rap music.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Other African musical traditions also involve strings, horns, and very few poly-rhythms.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Music from the eastern Sahel and along the Nile, among the Nilo-Saharan, made extensive use of strings and horns in ancient times.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Dancing involves swaying body movements and footwork.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Among the Khoisans extensive use of string instruments with emphasis on footwork.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Modern Sub-Saharan African music has been influenced by music from the New World (Jazz, Salsa, Rhythm and Blues etc.).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Popular styles include Mbalax in Senegal and Gambia, Highlife in Ghana, Zoblazo in Côte d'Ivoire, Makossa in Cameroon, Soukous in the Democratic Republic of Congo, Kizomba in Angola, and Xhosa music in South Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] New World styles like Salsa, R&B/Rap, Reggae, and Zouk also have widespread popularity.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Like the musical genres of the Nile Valley and the Horn of Africa, North African music has close ties with Middle Eastern music and utilizes similar melodic modes (*maqamat*).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] It has a considerable range, from the music of ancient Egypt to the Berber and the Tuareg music of the desert nomads.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The region's art music has for centuries followed the outline of Arabic and Andalusian classical music.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Its popular contemporary genres include the Algerian Raï.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Somali music is typically pentatonic, using five pitches per octave in contrast to a heptatonic (seven note) scale such as the major scale.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In Ethiopia, the Amhara music of the highlands uses a fundamental modal system called *qenet*, of which there are four main modes: *tezeta*, *bati*, *ambassel*, and *anchihoy*.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Three additional modes are variations on the above: tezeta minor, bati major, and bati minor.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Some songs take the name of their qenet, such as tizita, a song of reminiscence.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Africa is home to approximately one-third of the world's languages, anywhere between 1000 and 2000 languages.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The Niger-Congo languages inhabit Western, Central, Eastern and Southern Africa this includes the Bantu language.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Nilo-Saharan in parts of the Sahara and the Sahel and parts of Eastern Africa, and Khoisan (indigenous minorities of Southern Africa).
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Nilo-Saharan gathers approximately 140 languages with some eleven million speakers scattered in Central and Eastern Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Last but not least is the Khoisan family with between 40 - 70 members.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Believed to be the oldest of the four language families, it is the smallest of the four and is found mainly in Southern Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The continent of Africa speaks hundreds of languages, and if dialects spoken by various ethnic groups are also included, the number is much higher.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] These languages and dialects do not have the same importance: some are spoken by only a few hundred people, others are spoken by millions.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The most widely spoken languages of Africa, Swahili (100 million), Hausa (38 million), Yoruba (20 million), Amharic (20 million), Igbo (21 million), and Fula (13 million), belong mostly to the Niger-Congo family.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Very few countries of Africa use any single language, and for this reason, several official languages coexist, African and European.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Some Africans speak various European languages such as English, Spanish, French, Portuguese, Italian, German and Dutch.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] The official languages of the African Union and all its institutions shall be Arabic, English, French, Portuguese, Spanish, Kiswahili and any other African language.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Sports in Africa is organized, with many sports having professional leagues.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Association football (also known as soccer) is the most popular sport in almost all African countries.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Some East African nations, such as Kenya and Ethiopia, are very dominant at long-distance running, whilst North African countries such as Algeria, Egypt, Morocco and Tunisia are dominant in handball.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Rugby union and golf are reasonably popular in a few African countries, though rugby union is very popular in South Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] In 2010, South Africa became the first African nation to host the FIFA World Cup.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African cultures have had profound influences on the rest of the world through West African cultural traditions that were brought to the Americas and the Caribbean during the Trans-Atlantic Slave Trade, as well as later immigration of people from throughout Africa.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] African cultures, which originated on the continent of Africa, have several distinct differences than that of Black culture, which originated by African Americans in the United States after they were stripped of most of their own African cultures during enslavement.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Some differences are that African cultures retain tribal affairs to only be worn during specific events, hand carvings, tribal masks and dances whereas Black culture is *ethnic* to African Americans such as hip hop, jazz, hamboning and soul food.
[src:banana-fritter/african-culture] Though some Africanisms were retained in Black culture of the United States, most of Black American culture and history was created by Black Americans.
[src:banana-fritter/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:banana-fritter/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:banana-fritter/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:banana-fritter/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] A **banana fritter** is a fritter made by deep frying battered banana or plantain in hot cooking oil.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] It is a common dish across Southeast Asia, Madagascar, and South India.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Banana fritters are a traditional snack in Brunei, where they are called *cucur pisang*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are similar to *pisang goreng* in Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] *Cucur pisang madu*, a variant of *cucur pisang* made with honey, are popular as a light afternoon meal (*minum petang*).
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Khmer, banana fritters are called *num chek chien* (នំចេកចៀន; lit.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are made by dipping flattened bananas in a thick mixture of rice flour, sesame seeds, egg whites and coconut milk seasoned with salt and sugar and deep frying them in hot oil until crispy and golden.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The Cambodian banana fritters are more savoury than sweet and are often eaten as a snack with coconut ice cream as a popular accompaniment.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] A famous banana fritter shop in Cambodia is *Chek Chean Pises* operating since 2000 that has two locations in Phnom Penh – at Mao Tse Tong Boulevard and Kampuchea Krom Boulevard.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In the state of Kerala, banana fritters hold particular cultural and culinary significance and are commonly referred to as *pazham pori* or *ethakka appam*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are typically prepared using ripe *nendran* bananas, which give the fritters a distinctive flavor and texture.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Unlike many other types of fritters, they are traditionally served on their own often as an evening snack accompanied by tea and are not typically paired with curries or side dishes.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Indonesia, banana fritters are commonly known as *pisang goreng*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are often sold by street vendors, In Indonesia *pisang goreng* are deep fried in ample of cooking oil; they might be coated with batter or not.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Plantain is often used instead of banana.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Traditionally, some cultivars of banana such as *pisang raja*, *pisang tanduk* and *pisang kepok* are the most popular kinds of banana used for pisang goreng.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] These banana cultivars have a mild sweet and sour flavor and firm texture that will not crumble upon being fried.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] *Pisang raja* however, has a softer texture and a fragrant aroma.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The banana is often battered and then deep fried in ample palm oil.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Pisang goreng might be battered or plain deep fried.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The batter most commonly uses a combination of flour, either wheat, rice flour, tapioca or bread crumbs.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Several recipes might add coconut milk or milk and vanilla extract into the batter to add aroma.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Most traditional street vendors will then sell them as is, without any additional ingredients or toppings.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] However, more upscale coffee shops, cafes and restaurants serve more sophisticated *pisang goreng* sprinkled with powdered sugar, cinnamon sugar, cheese, jam, condensed milk, chocolate or vanilla ice cream.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Indonesia, it is consumed as a snack to accompany tea or coffee, either in the morning or late afternoon break.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Traditional *warung kopi* (local coffee shops) often offer *pisang goreng* and other snacks, including fritters and *kue* to accompany coffee or tea.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Banana fritters along other kinds of fritters are sold on travelling carts or by street vendors throughout Indonesia.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Other than pisang goreng, various kinds of ingredients are battered and deep fried such as tempeh, *mendoan*, tofu (*tahu goreng*), oncom, sweet potato, cassava chunk, cassava tapai, tapioca (*cireng*), vegetables (*bakwan*) and breadfruit.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Every region in Indonesia has developed various recipe for *pisang goreng* with a variety of different names, ingredients and cooking techniques.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Bali for example, *pisang goreng* is called *godoh biu*, in West Java it is called *cau goreng*, in Java *gedhang goreng*, in Sibolga *pisang rakit* and in Pontianak *pisang kipas*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Refers to banana cut in the shape of a fan, battered, and deep fried.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] , but with a different batter composition and a different frying technique.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] granules in the coating, and resulting in a sweet, fragrant aroma.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] fried banana", honey is added into the batter, and prior to serving honey is drizzled upon the fried banana.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The color is rather dark due to the caramelised honey.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] prior to frying, creating a crunchy texture on the outside similar to pastry skin, while the banana inside remains moist and soft.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] condensed milk, folded and deep fried in a similar fashion to making spring rolls.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Literally meaning "naked fried banana", it is fried without any batter.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] are the most suitable banana cultivars to be fried without batter.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] , a spicy chili paste made of smoked roa fish and fresh chilies.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Madagascar, where it is called *mofo akondro*, it consists of a whole or sliced banana—most often a cooking banana or a plantain—that is simply peeled and then dipped in a fluid, sticky batter.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] This batter, which serves as a coating, is traditionally made from wheat or rice flour, eggs, water or milk, and optionally sugar and a hint of vanilla.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The coated banana is then immersed in a bath of hot oil and fried until the exterior is golden and crispy, and the banana inside is cooked and tender.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Once fried, mofo akondro is primarily sold as street food.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] It is offered at a modest price by independent vendors, who sell it hot from market stalls or along busy thoroughfares, often to be eaten on the go as a quick and energizing snack.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Malaysia and Singapore, banana fritters are commonly known in the Malay language as *pisang goreng*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Other names may include *cekodok pisang* and *jemput-jemput pisang*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The style of banana fritters commonly found in these countries is made by deep frying battered plantain in hot oil.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] It is typically consumed as a snack in the morning and afternoon.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are often sold by street vendors, although it is also offered as a product at storefronts, dining establishments as well as Singapore's hawker centres.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Johor, Malaysia, **pisang goreng** is commonly served with **sambal kicap**, a spicy soy sauce dip that adds a savory and fiery twist to the traditional fried banana fritters.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] A dish of banana fritter cooked in thick, spicy fish sauce and served with rice is claimed to have been a favourite dish of the former royal family of Myanmar.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] There are numerous fried banana dishes in Philippines.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are almost always made from saba bananas, a native cooking banana that is widely used in Filipino cuisine.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] *Pritong saging* are fried saba bananas (without batter) usually served with sugar or syrup.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Bananas cooked with batter are a different dish known as *maruya*, which are more commonly made mashed or sliced very thinly and spread into a fan shape.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] However, the most common Filipino street food dishes made from banana are banana cue and *turon*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Banana cue are fried bananas coated with caramelized sugar and served on skewers; while *turon* is a type of fried dessert *lumpia* unique to the Philippines and is cooked in a crepe wrapper.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] The word *kluai* in Thai means "banana", and *khaek* means "guest" and is a colloquialism used for Indians, Muslims or Hindus — who may have provided a recipe on which these fritters were based.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] One area famous for *kluai khaek* in Bangkok is around Lan Luang Intersection to Chakkraphatdi Phong Intersection, where it is referred to as Nang Loeng in the Pom Prap Sattru Phai District.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] Here, there are many *kluai khaek* shops, whose sellers wear aprons of different colours.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They walk down the street carrying bags of bananas and sell to drivers passing through.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In February 2018, Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA) banned this type of trade on the streets.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Suriname, this snack is also known as *bakabana* (meaning fried banana in Surinamese).
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] In Vietnamese, banana fritters are called *chuối chiên*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] They are based on the French dessert *banana flambée*.
[src:banana-fritter/banana-fritter] After deep frying, Vietnamese banana fritters are drizzled with rum or rice wine and ignited to further crisp them.
